[Student "S"]
{North is to play 3NT. East leads the \S5, West plays the \SQ.

Winners:   \S=1  \H=2  \D=2  \C=3  Total = 8

Before worrying about where that one winner is going to come from you need to decide what to do with the opening lead. A good guideline is to hold up unless you fear a switch. Here, with all other suits well protected you would welcome a switch, so you let West win the \SQ. West then plays the \S8. Do you hold up again?

It probably doesn't matter, but since you cannot possibly win more than 10 tricks you might just as well hold up again. East wins the \SJ then plays the \S3. West discards a \H on the third \S.

OK, now it is time to figure out where that extra trick is coming from. Not much figuring is needed, it must come from the \D suit. Since you are missing 5 cards including the Queen, the odds favor a finesse over playing for the drop. And, since you have the option of finessing either defender are you going to finesse into the one who can set you or into the safe one?

Silly question. Of course you play the \DK from your hand, then a small \D finessing dummy's \D10, which wins the trick - and the game - and the overtrick.

Actually the odds slightly favored West holding the \DQ because West started with only 2 \Ss compared to East's 5 \Ss. Therefore West had 11 spaces which could hold the \DQ whereas East only had 8 spaces.

But in a situation like this you don't play odds. By finessing East you guaranteed making the contract even if the finesse lost because West had no more \Ss. Even a losing \D finesse would have established the one trick you needed.}
[Play "W"]S5

